ge – a sociohistorical perspective on scribes, readers, and networks in medieval Britain -- t14 Challenges of multiglossia: scribes and the emergence of substandard Judaeo- Arabic registers -- t15 Variation in a Norwegian sixteenthcentury scribal community -- t16 Language change induced by written codes: a case of Old Kanembu and Kanuri dialects -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe majority of our evidence for language change in pre-modern times comes from the written output of scribes. The present volume deals with a variety of aspects of language change and focuses on the role of scribes. The individual articles, which treat different theoretical and empirical issues, reflect a broad cross-linguistic and cross-cultural diversity. The languages that are represented cover a broad spectrum, and the empirical data come from a wide range of sources. This book provides a wealth of new data and new perspectives on old problems, and it raises new questions about the actual mechanisms of language change.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 4aSprachwandel. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aHistorical Linguistics.  aLanguage Variation and Change.  aRegisters.  aScribes.  aSociolinguistics.1 aBeinhoff, Bettina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeinhoff, Bettina, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBerg, Ivar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBergs, Alexander, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBondarev, Dmitry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBusse, Anja, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/c